00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:05.800
BORIS DEBIC: Welcome,
everybody, to one more Talks

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:07.190
at Google event.

00:00:07.190 --> 00:00:11.710
It is my extreme pleasure to
welcome today Dr. William J.

00:00:11.710 --> 00:00:12.980
Perry.

00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:18.870
The occasion is the publication
of his autobiographical book,

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:22.310
"My Journey at the
Nuclear Brink,"

00:00:22.310 --> 00:00:25.900
which also covers
in detail a topic

00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:29.820
that we will discuss
among other topics today,

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:33.000
which is one of
nuclear disarmament

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.580
and the security in
general in today's world.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:41.070
I'm not going to give a lengthy
introduction of Mr. Perry,

00:00:41.070 --> 00:00:45.220
because you all know how to
use the Google search engine.

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:48.450
But I will read
from a forward which

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:51.340
was written by his
colleague, former Secretary

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:57.670
of State George P. Shultz,
and it is in the book.

00:00:57.670 --> 00:01:00.320
Throughout his life
and work, William Perry

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:04.470
has distinguished himself as
a man of high intelligence,

00:01:04.470 --> 00:01:10.140
absolute integrity, rare vision,
remarkable accomplishment,

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:13.790
and an unwavering
sense of humanity.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:15.870
Evidence of these
attributes is vividly

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:18.270
apparent in the gripping
stories contained

00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:23.600
in these memoir chronicling
Bill's extraordinary efforts.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:26.350
I would also like
to mention here,

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:31.550
among all the honors that he
was given throughout life,

00:01:31.550 --> 00:01:33.480
probably one of the
most prestigious

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:38.050
would be the Presidential Medal
of Freedom, the United States

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:44.220
highest award for a civilian.

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:47.560
And when he was presented
with this award,

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:50.180
President Clinton
said, "Bill Perry

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:54.380
may will be recorded as the most
productive, effective Secretary

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:58.510
of Defense the United
States ever had."

00:01:58.510 --> 00:02:01.580
General John Shalikashvili,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs

00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:04.160
of Staff, offered
this assessment

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:07.300
of this extraordinary
public servant.

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:10.449
"Yes, he's a man of vast talent.

00:02:10.449 --> 00:02:13.000
Yes, he's a man
of enormous energy

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.440
and infectious enthusiasm.

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:19.750
Yes, he's a man of great caring
for those who wear our nation's

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:22.570
uniform and for their families.

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:27.040
But he's first and foremost a
man of unshakable character.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:29.920
He's a man who will
do what is right,

00:02:29.920 --> 00:02:32.220
no matter what the price."

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:36.520
Please join me in welcoming
Dr. Perry to Google.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:38.796
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:45.990
So I was originally
planning to do

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:50.320
the introduction of
your younger years,

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:54.880
because we want to
connect, in this show,

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:56.700
with the younger
audiences and make

00:02:56.700 --> 00:03:03.080
them aware of a grave threat
to our overall security.

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:06.820
But this weekend's
events forced us

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:10.970
into perhaps yet
another territory

00:03:10.970 --> 00:03:15.590
that you have covered
in your long career.

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:16.650
Can you comment?

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:21.740
Or do you have any
views on this latest

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:27.010
of the events, which was
the launch of a rocket

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:30.340
by North Korea?

00:03:30.340 --> 00:03:31.430
WILLIAM PERRY: Yeah.

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:36.600
I spent a lot of
time in the '90s

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:39.550
with the main mission of trying
to keep North Korea from going

00:03:39.550 --> 00:03:44.220
nuclear for a lot of reasons.

00:03:44.220 --> 00:03:47.760
Well, I failed.

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:50.990
And the consequence
of that failure

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:52.530
are yet to be played
out, but we see

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:56.490
some of the consequences,
intermediate consequences.

00:03:56.490 --> 00:04:01.310
And they've already had a number
of nuclear tests, at least

00:04:01.310 --> 00:04:04.770
three of which were successful.

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:08.000
And they have been building
missiles for a long time now.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.440
The missiles up to this point
are medium range missiles.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:15.070
They threaten South Korea.

00:04:15.070 --> 00:04:16.010
They threaten Japan.

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:17.635
They do not threaten
the United States.

00:04:19.990 --> 00:04:24.060
With their satellite
launch, which

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:27.540
is no problem in and of
itself, but of course,

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:30.670
to get the satellite into orbit,
you have to use a launcher.

00:04:30.670 --> 00:04:33.920
And the launcher is
essentially an ICBM.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:35.800
So while testing the
satellite, they're

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:41.140
also testing the early
stages of an ICBM.

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:43.837
If they perfect that, which
they have said they plan to do,

00:04:43.837 --> 00:04:46.170
then they will have a missile
that can strike the United

00:04:46.170 --> 00:04:47.070
States as well.

00:04:47.070 --> 00:04:50.895
Even so, this is nothing
if the warhead on it

00:04:50.895 --> 00:04:52.370
is high explosive.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:54.550
The real danger of a
missile is not the missile.

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:59.070
It's the fact that it could
carry a nuclear warhead.

00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:01.750
So their nuclear tests are
really of more concern to us

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:04.000
than the missile tests.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.700
The best judgment
of the people I

00:05:05.700 --> 00:05:09.605
know who are really expert in
the field of nuclear explosions

00:05:09.605 --> 00:05:12.240
and development
of nuclear weapons

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.220
believe that the North
Koreans at this point,

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:17.620
while they have a
successful nuclear bomb,

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:20.120
do not have one that
could be compact enough

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:25.730
to be put into a warhead,
that it might take one or two

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:29.260
more nuclear tests before
they would be able to verify

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:32.080
that kind of a design.

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:34.100
So we're perhaps
one or two tests,

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:35.850
nuclear tests, away,
and maybe another one

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:39.720
or two satellite
or ICBM launches

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.340
away from them having a
nuclear ICBM which could

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:45.270
threaten the United States.

00:05:45.270 --> 00:05:48.580
So it begins to be a
serious issue for us.

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:52.270
BORIS DEBIC: Dr. Perry, I
wanted to go back on the track

00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:57.280
that I originally had in mind
for our discussion today.

00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.920
Can you tell us a little
bit about your younger age,

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:02.770
when you were like
perhaps the younger

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.830
members of our audience.

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.480
And specifically,
I've heard that you've

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:13.260
been in Hiroshima after
the first explosions there.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:16.529
What were your impressions
at that young age?

00:06:16.529 --> 00:06:18.320
WILLIAM PERRY: Well,
I was actually younger

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:21.930
then than most of you.

00:06:21.930 --> 00:06:25.940
I was 14, when a
young man, a friend

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:30.170
came rushing into the room
and said, we are at war.

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:32.702
The Japanese have just
bombed Pearl Harbor.

00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:39.350
This is one of these epiphany
events, where you remember

00:06:39.350 --> 00:06:41.930
a few decades later
just where you were,

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:44.020
what you were
thinking, and so on.

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:49.030
What I was thinking at the time,
remember, I was 14 years old,

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:51.190
was that I was afraid the
war was going to be over

00:06:51.190 --> 00:06:52.780
before I could realize
my dream, which

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:55.630
was to be an Army
Air Corps pilot

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:58.120
and participate in the war.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:07:02.090
That's what a 14-year-old
was thinking of that news.

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:05.300
As it turned out, I was right.

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:09.820
The peace treaty was signed
in September of 1945,

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:13.630
when I turned 18
in October 1945.

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:16.070
So I just missed it.

00:07:16.070 --> 00:07:19.970
I did then sign up for
the Army Engineers,

00:07:19.970 --> 00:07:24.290
and was assigned to the
army of occupation in Japan.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:31.810
I spent two months in Tokyo, and
then almost a year in Okinawa.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:38.130
What I saw in Tokyo, in Okinawa
changed my view altogether

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:43.220
about the glamor and
the glory of war.

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.780
Tokyo, when I was
there, was in ruins.

00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:49.980
There was more damage
and more people

00:07:49.980 --> 00:07:52.810
killed than in
Hiroshima, actually,

00:07:52.810 --> 00:07:56.320
as a result of thousands
and thousands of fire bombs

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.000
dropped over a
period of two years.

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:05.090
And nothing I had read or
heard prepared before me

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:10.220
for just the shock of walking
through the streets of Tokyo

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:14.590
and seeing what was left
of this once great city.

00:08:14.590 --> 00:08:18.372
When I got to Okinawa just
two months later, Okinawa,

00:08:18.372 --> 00:08:19.830
you may not know
the history of it,

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:24.220
but it was the site of the last
great battle of World War II.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:29.600
To give you some
metric on it, there

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:34.130
were 100,000 Japanese
soldiers defending Okinawa.

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:37.809
When the battle was
over a few months later,

00:08:37.809 --> 00:08:40.130
there were fewer than 10,000.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:45.140
90% of them, 90,000
Japanese soldiers

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:49.904
died, not just were wounded,
they died in that battle, 90%.

00:08:49.904 --> 00:08:51.320
Either they were
killed in battle,

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:53.940
or they committed suicide.

00:08:53.940 --> 00:09:02.020
Another 100,000 civilians,
and about 15,000 or 20,000

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:02.610
Americans.

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:05.300
Most of the American
deaths, by the way,

00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:07.140
were the result of
kamikaze attacks,

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:11.270
suicide attacks on our ships.

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:13.730
When I landed, when
our ship landed

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:17.650
at Naha, which is the
capital of Okinawa,

00:09:17.650 --> 00:09:20.020
there was not a
building left standing.

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:23.670
It was a city about
the size of San Jose.

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:25.230
Nothing was left standing.

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:30.140
The people who survived
were living in rubble.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:33.690
So that was my first exposure
to what war is really like,

00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:38.090
not what you read about what
you hear about in speeches.

00:09:38.090 --> 00:09:41.060
I saw all those
scenes of destruction,

00:09:41.060 --> 00:09:44.010
and then I reflected
on Hiroshima.

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:51.110
This is what can be done
with 1,000 pound bombs.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:54.250
In the case of Tokyo,
thousands of them,

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:58.500
over a two year period, and
with thousands of bombers

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:05.710
delivering them-- the
same result in Hiroshima,

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:11.220
in an instant, one airplane
and one bomb, just one bomb.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:13.940
And even at the
tender age of 18,

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:19.160
I understood this
changed everything.

00:10:19.160 --> 00:10:22.480
Einstein had already
said that the advent

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.100
of the nuclear bomb,
everything has changed,

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:30.010
except the way we think.

00:10:30.010 --> 00:10:35.490
But what I saw in Japan,
Tokyo and Okinawa, even at 18,

00:10:35.490 --> 00:10:38.580
my thinking did begin to change.

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:43.960
I began to understand
the vast significance

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:46.950
of the role of nuclear weapons,
how they change everything,

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:51.750
certainly about the way warfare
will ever be waged used again,

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:54.070
and certainly
putting an imperative

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:58.329
that they must never,
ever be used again.

